nd":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irsko"},"da":{"1389–":"1389–Afdød","1389–Male":"1389–Afdød","1394–Female":"1394–Afdød","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irland"},"nl":{"1389–":"1389–Overleden","1389–Male":"1389–Overleden","1394–Female":"1394–Overleden","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ierland"},"en":{"1389–":"1389–Deceased","1389–Male":"1389–Deceased","1394–Female":"1394–Deceased","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Brien","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Dermot, Liam, Brigid, Declan, Donovan, John Patrick, Kieran, Colm, Donal, Brennan, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Briain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Brian</i>’, a personal name probably based on the element <i>bre-</i> ‘hill’, with the transferred sense ‘eminence’, i.e. ‘exalted one’. See also   Bryan  . In Ireland there has also been some confusion with   O'Byrne   (see   Byrne  ).","History: This name is borne in particular by one of the greatest of Irish septs, descendants of Brian Boru, who rose to the high kingship of Ireland in 1002."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Brion","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O'Bryon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish William Kevin.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"Bryan","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bryant  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Briain</b>, see   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O'Briant","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Brien  , with excrescent <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"O'Bryant","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"McBrien","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Seamus.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Briain</b> ‘son of Brian’. See   O'Brien   and   Bryan  ."]},{"name":"O'Brian","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O'Bryan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish James Patrick, Padraic.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]}]},{"name":"Brian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Irish origin: perhaps from an Old Celtic word meaning ‘high’ or ‘noble’. The name has been perennially popular in Ireland, in particular on account of the fame of  Brian Boru  (Gaelic <i>Brian Bóroimhe</i>) (  <i>c.</i> 940–1014 ), a warrior who was credited with driving the Vikings from Ireland and who eventually became high king of Ireland. In the Middle Ages it was relatively common in East Anglia, where it was introduced by Breton settlers, and in northern England, where it was introduced by Scandinavians from Ireland. It was quite popular in Yorkshire in the early 16th century, largely because it had long been a family name among the Stapletons, who had Irish connections. They first used it after  Sir Gilbert Stapleton  married  Agnes , the daughter of the great northern baron  Sir Brian fitzAlan . In Gaelic Scotland it was at first borne exclusively by members of certain professional families of Irish origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Bryan","meanings":["Variant of   Brian  , influenced by the usual spelling of the associated surname."]}]},{"name":"Dubh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Eve</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Brian Dubh macConchobaig O'Brien was born in 1389, in Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland as the son of Conchobhar macMathghamhna O'Brien, King of Thomond. He married Mrs. Margaret Brian Dubh O'Kennedy in 1414, in Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1389–":"1389–Surnud","1389–Male":"1389–Surnud","1394–Female":"1394–Surnud","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1389–":"1389–Kuollut","1389–Male":"1389–Kuollut","1394–Female":"1394–Kuollut","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1389–":"1389–Décédé","1389–Male":"1389–Décédé","1394–Female":"1394–Décédée","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Brian Dubh macConchobaig O'Brien est né en 1389, à Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irlande, fils de Conchobhar macMathghamhna O'Brien, King of Thomond. Il a épousé Mrs. Margaret Brian Dubh O'Kennedy en 1414, à Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irlande. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1389–":"1389–Verstorben","1389–Male":"1389–Verstorben","1394–Female":"1394–Verstorben","1415–1502":"1415–1502","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1502":"1502","1389":"1389","1394":"1394","1360":"1360","Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Irland","lifeSummary":"Bri